                        <par_12
                            jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                            sling:resourceType="wcm/foundation/components/parsys">
                            <container4
                                cq:styleIds="[1653545847150,1653242825678,1653545825687,1653545835982]"
                                jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/container/v2/container">
                                <title2
                                    cq:styleIds="[1659545825678,1651545824678,1651545825694]"
                                    jcr:lastModified="{Date}2024-03-20T10:38:29.386-04:00"
                                    jcr:lastModifiedBy="VALENSX5"
                                    jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                    jcr:title="Rebels with a cause"
                                    sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/title/v2/title"
                                    type="h2"
                                    variant="h"/>
                                <text2
                                    cq:styleIds="[1659545825678,1659545835858]"
                                    jcr:lastModified="{Date}2023-09-08T12:23:29.586-04:00"
                                    jcr:lastModifiedBy="chiucx"
                                    jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                    sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/text/v2/text"
                                    text="&lt;p>Andrew Petros and Phil Hajduk are rebels, but you might not know it by looking at them.&lt;/p>&#xd;&#xa;&lt;p>As researchers who spent their careers—34 years and 24 years, respectively—developing medicines at AbbVie, they were trained to follow the rules and principles of science: ideas that are accepted to be true, until someone proves them wrong.&lt;/p>&#xd;&#xa;&lt;p>While science takes discipline, pioneering research relies on the ability to see where rules need to be challenged—or even broken. It takes bold risks and embarking on unchartered paths all in the name of transforming treatment options for patients. If Petros, Hajduk and their colleagues had been afraid to bet on themselves and stuck to conventional scientific “rules,” they wouldn’t have accomplished their goal: finding a way to force cancer cells to die.&lt;br>&#xd;&#xa;&lt;/p>&#xd;&#xa;"
                                    textIsRich="true"/>
                                <separator_copy_copy
                                    cq:styleIds="[1662756423318]"
                                    jcr:created="{Date}2022-11-16T10:43:45.922-05:00"
                                    jcr:createdBy="chiucx"
                                    jcr:lastModified="{Date}2022-11-16T10:43:45.922-05:00"
                                    jcr:lastModifiedBy="chiucx"
                                    jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                    sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/separator/v2/separator"/>
                                <title2_copy
                                    cq:styleIds="[1659545825678,1651545824678,1651545825694]"
                                    jcr:lastModified="{Date}2024-03-20T10:38:36.066-04:00"
                                    jcr:lastModifiedBy="VALENSX5"
                                    jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                    jcr:title="Rule #1: Cancer cells don’t die"
                                    sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/title/v2/title"
                                    type="h2"
                                    variant="h"/>
                                <text2_copy
                                    cq:styleIds="[1659545825678,1659545835858]"
                                    jcr:lastModified="{Date}2023-09-08T12:24:06.280-04:00"
                                    jcr:lastModifiedBy="chiucx"
                                    jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                    sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/text/v2/text"
                                    text="&lt;p>Back in the early 1990s, Petros and Hajduk were both discovery scientists at AbbVie (then Abbott). They were focused on understanding apoptosis, or programmed cell death, and mapping structures of proteins that were important to this cellular process.&lt;/p>&#xd;&#xa;&lt;p>Cancer cells differ from healthy cells in several ways, but the key difference is their ability to avoid death. All cells in the body are programmed to self-destruct at pre-determined times—when they get old, when their function is compromised or when they are no longer needed. This function is short-circuited in cancer cells, and without the ability to die, they continue to grow uncontrolled.&lt;/p>&#xd;&#xa;&lt;p>This resistance to death was a well-known hallmark of cancer cells. What to do about it, though, remained a mystery.&lt;/p>&#xd;&#xa;&lt;p>The AbbVie team had a theory. If they could find a treatment that targeted proteins known to be important in the apoptotic process, they might be able to reset the cell-death process and induce cancer cell death.&lt;/p>&#xd;&#xa;&lt;p>But like all uncharted areas of research, this work brought more questions than answers. With the right team, AbbVie researchers forged into the unknown and disproved some widely-held scientific beliefs in the process.&lt;br>&#xd;&#xa;&lt;/p>&#xd;&#xa;"
                                    textIsRich="true"/>
                            </container4>
                            <quote_copy_copy
                                cq:styleIds="[1000000000000]"
                                jcr:created="{Date}2022-11-16T17:03:32.882-05:00"
                                jcr:createdBy="chiucx"
                                jcr:lastModified="{Date}2023-09-08T14:04:24.481-04:00"
                                jcr:lastModifiedBy="chiucx"
                                jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/quote"
                                attributionName="Philip Hajduk, Ph.D."
                                attributionTitle="VP, R&amp;D information research, AbbVie"
                                quote="Instead of trying to find all the pieces at once, we thought, let’s look here first and find a molecule that binds here. Then, we can find an adjacent site later.”"
                                quoteType="regular"
                                textSize="h0"/>
                            <container
                                cq:styleIds="[1653545825687,1653545847150,1653242825678,1653545835982]"
                                jcr:created="{Date}2023-06-08T12:44:53.269-04:00"
                                jcr:createdBy="SCHAFSM"
                                jcr:lastModified="{Date}2023-06-08T12:44:53.269-04:00"
                                jcr:lastModifiedBy="SCHAFSM"
                                jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/container/v2/container">
                                <separator_copy_copy_
                                    cq:styleIds="[1662756423318]"
                                    jcr:created="{Date}2022-11-16T10:43:45.922-05:00"
                                    jcr:createdBy="chiucx"
                                    jcr:lastModified="{Date}2022-11-16T10:43:45.922-05:00"
                                    jcr:lastModifiedBy="chiucx"
                                    jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                    sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/separator/v2/separator"/>
                                <title2_copy_copy
                                    cq:styleIds="[1659545825678,1651545824678,1651545825694]"
                                    jcr:lastModified="{Date}2024-03-19T14:01:28.004-04:00"
                                    jcr:lastModifiedBy="VALENSX5"
                                    jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                    jcr:title="Rule #2: Some targets are just “undruggable”"
                                    sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/title/v2/title"
                                    type="h2"
                                    variant="h"/>
                                <text2_copy_copy
                                    cq:styleIds="[1659545825678,1659545835858]"
                                    jcr:lastModified="{Date}2023-09-08T13:38:13.858-04:00"
                                    jcr:lastModifiedBy="chiucx"
                                    jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                    sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/text/v2/text"
                                    text="&lt;p>As the researchers knew, several proteins are part of the apoptotic process, and while some of these proteins prevent cell death, others trigger it. These proteins communicate with each other in a complex system. At the time, most believed these proteins were too difficult to target with small-molecule medicines, leading many to consider them “undruggable” targets.&lt;/p>&#xd;&#xa;&lt;p>For one thing, the surfaces of these proteins are large and relatively featureless compared to a typical small molecule binding site. Additionally, the way these proteins interact is different from that of enzymes or kinases (enzymes that alter the biological function of proteins), which are more typical targets of small molecules.&lt;/p>&#xd;&#xa;&lt;p>“Thinking we could design a small-molecule inhibitor that could disrupt a protein-protein interaction was unprecedented at the time, but we believed there was a way,” says Petros, Ph.D., research fellow, AbbVie.&amp;nbsp;“We started by using high-powered analytical methods called nuclear magnetic resonance spectroscopy and X-ray crystallography to create a map of Bcl-xL, the easiest-to-access protein in the apoptotic process, so that we could figure out what ‘active’ sites on its surface we might be able to target with a medicine to block its function.”&lt;/p>&#xd;&#xa;&lt;p>Once the team had a map of the protein’s surface, they needed to find small molecules that could bind to, and inhibit, the function of these Bcl proteins on the surface of cancer cells.&lt;/p>&#xd;&#xa;&lt;p>“We took a step back to look at why protein-protein interactions were so difficult,” says Hajduk, Ph.D., vice president, R&amp;amp;D information research, AbbVie.&amp;nbsp;“Basically, we were looking for an existing molecule that was able to disrupt the interaction across multiple surface points—in a library of millions and millions of molecules.”&lt;/p>&#xd;&#xa;&lt;p>So, the team approached it like a jigsaw puzzle.&lt;/p>&#xd;&#xa;&lt;p>“Instead of trying to find all the pieces at once, we thought, let’s look here first and find a molecule that binds here. Then, we can find an adjacent site later,” Hajduk says. “And now you have a linear problem where you can solve problem one, then solve problem two, and then figure out how to hook all of these things together.”&lt;br>&#xd;&#xa;&lt;/p>&#xd;&#xa;"
                                    textIsRich="true"/>
                            </container>
                            <quote_copy
                                cq:styleIds="[1000000000000]"
                                jcr:created="{Date}2022-11-16T17:03:32.882-05:00"
                                jcr:createdBy="chiucx"
                                jcr:lastModified="{Date}2023-09-08T13:39:27.566-04:00"
                                jcr:lastModifiedBy="chiucx"
                                jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/quote"
                                attributionName="Andrew Petros, Ph.D."
                                attributionTitle="Research fellow, AbbVie"
                                quote="We had a problem. The right tool to solve the problem didn’t exist, so we invented the tool, which has become the industry standard.&quot;"
                                quoteType="regular"
                                textSize="h0"/>
                            <container4_copy
                                cq:styleIds="[1653545847150,1653242825678,1653545825687,1653545835982]"
                                jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/container/v2/container">
                                <separator_copy_copy
                                    cq:styleIds="[1662756423318]"
                                    jcr:created="{Date}2022-11-16T10:43:45.922-05:00"
                                    jcr:createdBy="chiucx"
                                    jcr:lastModified="{Date}2022-11-16T10:43:45.922-05:00"
                                    jcr:lastModifiedBy="chiucx"
                                    jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                    sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/separator/v2/separator"/>
                                <title2_copy
                                    cq:styleIds="[1659545825678,1651545824678,1651545825694]"
                                    jcr:lastModified="{Date}2024-03-19T14:02:09.558-04:00"
                                    jcr:lastModifiedBy="VALENSX5"
                                    jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                    jcr:title="Rule #3: If you don’t have equipment to do something, you just can’t do it"
                                    sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/title/v2/title"
                                    type="h2"
                                    variant="h"/>
                                <text2_copy
                                    cq:styleIds="[1659545825678,1659545835858]"
                                    jcr:lastModified="{Date}2023-09-08T12:28:29.040-04:00"
                                    jcr:lastModifiedBy="chiucx"
                                    jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                    sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/text/v2/text"
                                    text="&lt;p>Scientists use different methods of screening compounds to see which ones might bind to a particular target and how tightly they bind. Traditional high-throughput methods—ways that allowed scientists to screen large numbers of compounds quickly—worked well for enzyme and kinase targets, but not for proteins.&lt;/p>&#xd;&#xa;&lt;p>Not having the necessary tool might lead some to abandon the job. Instead, Petros, Hajduk and their team set out with a big ambition: invent it.&lt;/p>&#xd;&#xa;&lt;p>They created a technology called SAR by NMR (structure-activity relationships by nuclear magnetic resonance), which uses NMR spectroscopy—a way of measuring the interactions between molecules using radio waves—to identify very small organic molecules, or fragments, that bound weakly to the target protein.&lt;/p>&#xd;&#xa;&lt;p>When those fragments that bound to Bcl-xL were identified, the team again used NMR spectroscopy to gather structural information on how the fragments were binding to the protein. They could then use chemistry to link these weak binders together, producing a larger molecule which bound tighter to the Bcl-xL protein.&lt;/p>&#xd;&#xa;&lt;p>The new tool not only allowed the team to solve their mystery but has since helped researchers around the world create innovative new medicines for a range of diseases.&lt;/p>&#xd;&#xa;&lt;p>“SAR by NMR has become an industry standard tool for finding a starting point,” Petros says. “In fact, there are entire companies devoted to what’s now known as fragment-based drug discovery.”&lt;br>&#xd;&#xa;&lt;/p>&#xd;&#xa;"
                                    textIsRich="true"/>
                                <separator_copy_copy_
                                    cq:styleIds="[1662756423318]"
                                    jcr:created="{Date}2022-11-16T10:43:45.922-05:00"
                                    jcr:createdBy="chiucx"
                                    jcr:lastModified="{Date}2022-11-16T10:43:45.922-05:00"
                                    jcr:lastModifiedBy="chiucx"
                                    jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                    sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/separator/v2/separator"/>
                                <title2_copy_copy
                                    cq:styleIds="[1659545825678,1651545824678,1651545825694]"
                                    jcr:lastModified="{Date}2024-03-20T10:51:20.930-04:00"
                                    jcr:lastModifiedBy="VALENSX5"
                                    jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                    jcr:title="Rule #4: You must follow the rule of four"
                                    sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/title/v2/title"
                                    type="h2"
                                    variant="h"/>
                                <text2_copy_copy
                                    cq:styleIds="[1659545825678,1659545835858]"
                                    jcr:lastModified="{Date}2023-09-08T12:29:16.440-04:00"
                                    jcr:lastModifiedBy="chiucx"
                                    jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                    sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/text/v2/text"
                                    text="&lt;p>Formulated by Pfizer scientist Christopher Lipinski in 1997, the “Rule of Four” is a set of four molecular properties that help researchers determine whether a compound might be used as a medicine. A biologically active compound that has these four traits—certain chemical and physical properties ranging from how it’s absorbed in the body to how it’s excreted—tends to be associated with a greater chance of success in the clinic.&lt;/p>&#xd;&#xa;&lt;p>“When we’d mapped the Bcl-xL protein structure and had a sense of what we were dealing with, we knew we wouldn’t get a Rule of Four-compliant molecule because of the nature of the binding site. But in the end, our research showed it was possible to develop a non-rule-of-four-compliant molecule and have it still be efficacious,” Petros says. “Not one of the molecules we ended up studying in the clinic abided by the usual rules of drug development.”&lt;br>&#xd;&#xa;&lt;/p>&#xd;&#xa;"
                                    textIsRich="true"/>
                            </container4_copy>
